    "id": 237,
    "key": "998E9TZ5",
    "title": "Early self-organization of fission gas bubble superlattice formation in neutron-irradiated monolithic U-10Mo fuels",
    "date": "2023-05-00 2023-05",
    "journal": "Journal of Nuclear Materials",
    "doi": "10.1016/j.jnucmat.2023.154358",
    "abstract": "Self-organization of defect superlattices in far-from-equilibrium systems presents a promising way to mitigate swelling concerns in nuclear materials. The gas bubble superlattice (GBS) is a highly ordered, three-dimensional complex defect structure that can retain ﬁssion gasses in Uranium-Molybdenum (UMo) fuels. Transmission electron microscopy (TEM) investigation of monolithic U-10Mo fuel irradiated to 1.15 × 1021 ﬁssions/cm3 and 1.30 × 1021 ﬁssions/cm3 revealed that early-stage ordering prefer",
    "pdf_path": "/Volumes/openclaw记忆/Zotero_storage/storage/M9DCH6ZP/Smith et al. - 2023 - Early self-organization of fission gas bubble superlattice formation in neutron-irradiated monolithi.pdf",
